25:48.520 --> 25:54.520
So, I mean, that's why I try not to take job description as a gospel, although it's very tempting.

25:54.520 --> 25:58.520
Because you want to check all the boxes as many as you can, but it's just a guideline.

25:58.520 --> 26:03.520
Like, it's an educated guess as to what the new person might be doing, but it's still a guess.

26:03.520 --> 26:09.520
So, sorry, I'm going to the list here.

26:09.560 --> 26:21.560
So, I think what I've seen some people do, like, you start in open source, but then you step back, you take a different role, you do a non-open source role.

26:21.560 --> 26:25.560
I think some of you have done that in your career.

26:25.560 --> 26:34.560
Like, can you talk about that experience and why you, I don't know if you were forced to do that, or why did you just step away and what was it like coming back into open source?

26:34.600 --> 26:40.600
I've done it multiple times, I mean, three decades is a long time.

26:40.600 --> 26:51.600
I mean, some of it was layoffs, you know, it happens, but more of it was often, I mean, there's reasons like family health, there's reasons like kids,

26:51.600 --> 26:59.600
there's reasons like I took a break to do a PhD, you know, there's all kinds of good reasons to take a break, but another one is to avoid burnout.

26:59.640 --> 27:05.640
So, if you think you have to stay in the one project forever, you will work yourself and work yourself and work yourself.

27:05.640 --> 27:14.640
But if you recognize it's totally okay to just go away for a couple years and, you know, either come back to that project or a totally different project that excites you two years from now.

27:14.640 --> 27:27.640
Like, it feels less devastating to step aside from a project and you can do a well planned orderly handoff instead of a flame out burnout.

27:27.680 --> 27:34.680
If you push yourself all the way to flame out burnout, chances are you will never work in open source again because you burned yourself too far down.

27:34.680 --> 27:42.680
You can come back, but it's much, much harder than if you just recognize the signs and say, oh, you know, I should really take a couple years off and do something else.

27:42.680 --> 27:44.680
And then you come back revitalized.

27:44.680 --> 27:49.680
So, yeah, I actually, I highly recommend taking a break from time to time. It's a really good idea.

27:49.680 --> 27:51.680
Cool.

27:51.720 --> 27:54.720
Yeah, I've also had the occasional detour.

27:54.720 --> 28:02.720
I had one that was the company that I worked for, the politics around open source internally just got to be too much for me.

28:02.720 --> 28:09.720
And so I spent six months working in a, like, a market research department or something, something kind of random that I thought was a little bit interesting.

28:09.720 --> 28:20.720
But, you know, in the other way, I think that can help with, you know, burnout and just kind of, you know, doing something new is I've worked in loads of different open source communities.

28:20.760 --> 28:28.760
So, chaos is probably the one that I've worked in the longest because I've been working with these tools since before the, before the organization existed.

28:28.760 --> 28:39.760
But in a lot of cases, I've worked in, you know, kind of a series of open source projects based, frankly, on what the company that I was working for was particularly interested in.

28:39.760 --> 28:49.760
But the thing that I found was that in every time I switched from an open source community to another, I found that there was at least one person that I knew from a previous open source community.

28:49.800 --> 28:59.800
So even when you kind of bounce from community to community, there are usually other people that you know from previous lives in other communities.

29:01.800 --> 29:07.800
I do not have the experience yet. I'm still burning myself to learn the lesson.

29:07.800 --> 29:17.800
But to Don's point, I did see people, like, moving from one employer to the other, but still working in the same open source project.

29:17.840 --> 29:23.840
And also the popping up at another community and like, oh, hi.

29:23.840 --> 29:25.840
Like, you're here too. Cool.

29:25.840 --> 29:34.840
And it's just, it kind of shows you that the world gets a little bit smaller if you keep being involved in open source and you just know people.

29:34.840 --> 29:44.840
And the connections that you make will more likely to stay with you longer than in a corporate environment where you're just jumping, jumping companies.

29:44.880 --> 29:46.880
And that's a really nice experience.

29:46.880 --> 30:02.880
Even if I assume that even when you're taking a break and you come back and you see some familiar faces, but the project is new, that's kind of a nice mixture of I'm doing something new, but I don't have to make all new buddies to go from A to B.

30:02.880 --> 30:04.880
So yeah.

30:04.880 --> 30:06.880
Cool. So yeah.

30:06.920 --> 30:10.920
Yeah. So, I mean, I think earlier we were talking about like regrets or mistakes.

30:10.920 --> 30:14.920
I mean, the one I made personally was, I mean, I was working at Intel.

30:14.920 --> 30:19.920
We got reorg and then I had to stop working on open source, which was devastating.

30:19.920 --> 30:26.920
And then I think the mistake I made was I just spent time like sulking and being depressed.

30:26.920 --> 30:28.920
And I mean, that's fine.

30:28.960 --> 30:42.960
But what I should have done is do more productive and try to get engaged in the open source community somehow, find a different project, show up to meet ups, et cetera, et cetera, rather than feeling sorry for myself.

30:42.960 --> 30:49.960
So I think getting reorg then maybe getting laid off are two good examples.

30:50.000 --> 30:58.000
Like if you're a force away from like open source, like, you know, what advice do you have for, you know, maybe just stay engaged in the community somehow.

30:58.000 --> 31:00.000
I think nowadays it's easier.

31:00.000 --> 31:10.000
But, you know, what kind of approaches do you take to find a new community to join or like how do you keep up to date on what's happening out there?

31:10.000 --> 31:16.000
I have an example that's kind of slightly connecting to the questions.

31:16.040 --> 31:18.040
I will share it.

31:18.040 --> 31:30.040
I used to do trainings like how to contribute to OpenStack trainings one or two days before, prior to big events where a lot of people traveled to.

31:30.040 --> 31:36.040
And I met a lot of different people with very different motivations of why they were at that training.

31:36.040 --> 31:42.040
Some of them were just like it was free and then they were already there and it seemed interesting.

31:42.080 --> 31:49.080
And a lot of people kept asking like they do the training, they learn about the tools, the processes in the community.

31:49.080 --> 31:54.080
So what should they do next, what they should work on?

31:54.080 --> 31:58.080
And I always kept asking back like what are you interested in?

31:58.080 --> 32:02.080
Because I can point you to the low hanging fruit bugs.

32:02.080 --> 32:04.080
That's easy.

32:04.080 --> 32:10.080
But once you fix the bug and then you fix another one, then the third one is like why am I doing this in the first place?

32:10.120 --> 32:18.120
If you're not interested in the particular technology or you don't have a motivation to be at that particular place.

32:18.120 --> 32:25.120
So I would say that don't ever let anyone else tell you what you should do.

32:25.120 --> 32:28.120
Go where you feel passionate.

32:28.120 --> 32:33.120
Like learning, when you learn something new, where you're interested in the technology.

32:33.120 --> 32:39.120
And if you get involved then you will have the connections and then the job will come around as well.

32:39.160 --> 32:45.160
If you want a paid job that also works with that particular technology.

32:45.160 --> 32:54.160
So I would say that here make sure that you prioritize your interest and invest in yourself through that.

32:54.160 --> 32:58.160
I think it also partly goes back to the people.

32:58.160 --> 33:03.160
Like multiple times, we talked about other open source contributors moving from project to project.

33:03.160 --> 33:07.160
Like I was working at Canonical and when I left Canonical,

33:07.200 --> 33:11.200
a lot of other people that had also been at Canonical working on the OpenStack project.

33:11.200 --> 33:14.200
And I thought, that's interesting. What's that all about?

33:14.200 --> 33:16.200
And that is how I got involved in OpenStack.

33:16.200 --> 33:21.200
It was just by talking to other people and seeing what they were interested in now and kind of keeping those connections.

33:21.200 --> 33:30.200
So your network in open source can be really, really valuable in staying connected and finding out where the new things are and where you might want to keep working.

33:30.200 --> 33:31.200
Cool.

33:31.240 --> 33:34.240
Okay. I think we have about 13 minutes left.

33:34.240 --> 33:39.240
So I think I'll ask one more question and then leave the last 10 minutes for the audience.

33:39.240 --> 33:42.240
And I'm not going to hold any of you to this.

33:42.240 --> 33:48.240
I think earlier when I started, I felt pretty depressed for large parts of last year.

33:48.240 --> 33:55.240
Because I wasn't sure if this shift is unique or we're just dealing with another pendulum swing.

33:55.240 --> 33:59.240
So open source careers, in general, what's your outlook?

33:59.280 --> 34:05.280
I mean, to be honest, I think I'm a little bit more optimistic now than I was like middle of last year.

34:05.280 --> 34:07.280
Middle of last year just seemed daunting.

34:07.280 --> 34:11.280
And I just devastating to see a lot of my friends get laid off.

34:11.280 --> 34:16.280
But what are your thoughts on where things are headed?

34:16.280 --> 34:19.280
Or are we dealing with more of the same?

34:20.280 --> 34:22.280
Okay.

34:22.280 --> 34:24.280
I can go first.

34:24.320 --> 34:31.320
So as I work for an open source foundation that is a nonprofit organization,

34:31.320 --> 34:38.320
and I work with a lot of communities, I do see the effect still of where the economy is right now.

34:38.320 --> 34:43.320
However, at the same time, even just in the past two days in the co-located events,

34:43.320 --> 34:45.320
people are throwing out numbers.

34:45.320 --> 34:53.320
Like if we didn't have open source, then it would be like 4. something billion dollars to rebuild what we lost.

34:53.360 --> 34:58.360
And the trillions of dollars of demand that is driven by open source software.

34:58.360 --> 35:04.360
So those kind of numbers show that open source will not go away.

35:04.360 --> 35:11.360
So even if the economy is restructuring itself, companies will restructure themselves too.

35:11.360 --> 35:17.360
And I don't think that anyone really has a choice of not using open source software anymore.

35:17.360 --> 35:22.360
The software also needs to be maintained because otherwise you're not able to use that.

35:22.400 --> 35:31.400
Security is a high priority item in any single conversation that I've been participating in in the past few months.

35:31.400 --> 35:34.400
And maybe it's getting up to years now.

35:34.400 --> 35:37.400
So there's a lot to do in open source.

35:37.400 --> 35:42.400
It is also a model that is very sustainable if it's done right in terms of investment.

35:42.400 --> 35:46.400
So I think we will bounce back overall.

35:46.440 --> 35:56.440
And I think that the job market will have a lot of opportunities that are more directly focused on open source.

35:56.440 --> 36:02.440
And even, I think Alison mentioned that there isn't really a job that has nothing to do with open source anymore.

36:02.440 --> 36:05.440
It's just maybe isn't called out directly.

36:05.440 --> 36:08.440
But I'm optimistic.

36:08.440 --> 36:10.440
Yeah, I'm also optimistic.

36:10.480 --> 36:16.480
I do think that the pendulum has swung too far in the cutting of jobs.

36:16.480 --> 36:20.480
And in particular, I think some of the open source groups have been particularly bad hit.

36:20.480 --> 36:28.480
But I think it's not going to take companies long to realize that somebody has to do that work on the projects that they depend on.

36:28.480 --> 36:31.480
And so, you know, I work a lot with CNCF projects.

36:31.480 --> 36:38.480
Most of them are understaffed and they don't have enough resources to maintain the software over the long term.

36:38.520 --> 36:45.520
And I think that if they don't get more contributors coming back to those projects, because companies have pulled people off of some of those projects.

36:45.520 --> 36:50.520
And so many companies, their whole product line relies on a lot of these products.

36:50.520 --> 36:56.520
So I think they're going to quickly realize that their new features, their bug fixes, their things they're going to need in the software,

36:56.520 --> 37:00.520
that they're going to have to resource some of that.

37:00.520 --> 37:05.520
But the other trend that I find particularly promising as well is some of the alternative funding sources.

37:05.560 --> 37:12.560
So you look at groups like the sovereign tech fund out of Germany who are funding core infrastructure projects.

37:12.560 --> 37:14.560
You look at things like GitHub sponsors.

37:14.560 --> 37:21.560
You look at a lot of these other groups that have started funding individual projects, individual developers.

37:21.560 --> 37:28.560
And so I think that's also an interesting trend from a career and a job standpoint for open source.

37:28.560 --> 37:31.560
I don't know.

37:31.600 --> 37:39.600
From personal experience, I was laid off last year and I haven't looked too hard because I was having fun working full time on my volunteer open source projects.

37:39.600 --> 37:45.600
But I did see in the new year, towards the end of the year, it was a lot of, oh, this year it's totally blocked off.

37:45.600 --> 37:49.600
And in the beginning of the new year, it was like, we're hiring, we're hiring, we're hiring, we have a lot of spaces to fill.

37:49.600 --> 37:56.600
So if you think it's been a difficult year last year, look again because things are changing now.

37:56.640 --> 38:02.640
Cool. So I think cautiously optimistic is the phrase I like to borrow from the economists.

38:02.640 --> 38:05.640
So I think we can open up to audience questions.

38:05.640 --> 38:09.640
I don't know if we have a microphone for the audience or I can just bring one.

38:09.680 --> 38:13.680
Thanks. So I have a question for Ildiko.

38:13.680 --> 38:21.680
You mentioned earlier that when you are at events like this, you have to take advantage of getting to know people and to interact.

38:21.680 --> 38:29.680
So I'm also introvert. How do you get past the barrier of talking to strangers at an event like this?

38:29.720 --> 38:32.720
Not an easy question I know, but.

38:32.720 --> 38:37.720
Excellent question.

38:37.720 --> 38:41.720
I can only share my personal experience.

38:41.720 --> 38:46.720
To me, if I'm passionate about something that will push me through the first few seconds of awful experience,

38:46.720 --> 38:49.720
I can only share my personal experience.

38:49.720 --> 38:52.720
I can only share my personal experience.

38:52.760 --> 39:00.760
If I'm passionate about something that will push me through the first few seconds of awful experience.

39:00.760 --> 39:10.760
The other thing is that what I found is I have days when I just wake up and I'm feeling more social.

39:10.760 --> 39:13.760
And there are days when I can do whatever I want.

39:13.760 --> 39:19.760
I could write a script for myself before I walk up to a person who I don't know yet.

39:19.800 --> 39:23.800
And I would still be totally awkward.

39:23.800 --> 39:28.800
And I learned to say that it's okay.

39:28.800 --> 39:31.800
I have days like this and it is okay.

39:31.800 --> 39:39.800
I also started to kind of be a bit more open about this sometimes just telling the person, you know, I'm socially awkward sometimes.

39:39.800 --> 39:41.800
I'm not ashamed about it.

39:41.800 --> 39:44.800
So like I'm not afraid of putting it out on the table.

39:44.840 --> 39:50.840
And many times the other person can relate that, yeah, well, it's not easy for me either.

39:50.840 --> 39:57.840
And it's just so many examples I have where I said something like this and all of the sudden,

39:57.840 --> 40:04.840
that was like the icebreaker and the other person is also like, oh yeah, it is hard for me too.

40:04.840 --> 40:06.840
And then we have something to talk about.

40:06.840 --> 40:08.840
So it is hard.

40:08.840 --> 40:12.840
I know that it will drain me like after a conference like this.

40:12.880 --> 40:15.880
I need a few days to recover.

40:15.880 --> 40:28.880
My mother also knows that she should not call me like two, three days for two, three days because I will not be a pleasant experience on the phone necessarily.

40:28.880 --> 40:39.880
But yeah, you learn how the social interaction affects you and then you will also learn how to navigate yourself.

40:39.920 --> 40:49.920
So I can only encourage people to get through the first few awkward experiences and then build on what you learned about yourself.

40:51.920 --> 40:55.920
Yeah, I mean, just to build on that, like talking to strangers is hard, right?

40:55.920 --> 40:59.920
And I share some of Ildigo's like I tend to be a little socially awkward.

40:59.920 --> 41:03.920
But what helps me is to talk to people in more social situations.

41:03.960 --> 41:11.960
So you know, you're in line for a coffee or you're at one of the after parties or something where it's a little bit more social.

41:11.960 --> 41:13.960
And I just sort of have ways of coping with it.

41:13.960 --> 41:17.960
Like my question for people is always, you know, are you enjoying the conference?

41:17.960 --> 41:23.960
Or you know, and building on that like, oh, it was the favorite thing you saw today or what are you looking forward to tomorrow?

41:23.960 --> 41:30.960
So you're talking about the conference and you're also, you know, even if this person isn't all that interesting to you or working on the kind of the same things,

41:31.000 --> 41:36.000
maybe you learn something about what they found at the conference and what looks interesting to them.

41:36.000 --> 41:38.000
And it can be a good icebreaker.

41:38.000 --> 41:45.000
And you know, and then sometimes, you know, if you're standing in a group of people and you know, somebody else will chime in and then pretty soon you've got a conversation.

41:45.000 --> 41:51.000
But that's how I start. That's my coping strategy for awkward conversations with strangers.

41:51.000 --> 41:53.000
I'm also an extreme introvert.

41:53.000 --> 41:59.000
For me, it's about understanding that it's difficult for them too.

41:59.040 --> 42:04.040
So if I'm focused on trying to make them comfortable, I'm not thinking about how uncomfortable I am.

42:04.040 --> 42:06.040
And also just being super curious.

42:06.040 --> 42:09.040
Like, ooh, what do you do? What are you interested in?

42:09.040 --> 42:17.040
And like, I get so focused on whatever project they're involved in that, again, I just completely forget about my own awkwardness.

42:17.040 --> 42:24.040
But planning time off, like even in the middle of the conference, planning like half a day off, like, oh, I don't have a whole lot of talks I want to see right now.

42:24.040 --> 42:26.040
I'm just going to go back to the hotel.

42:26.080 --> 42:31.080
And it really helps because you recharge that introvert battery and then you're ready to deal with people again.

42:31.080 --> 42:47.080
I just want to say like plus thousand to that one because I think it took me years to be comfortable with saying I don't really need to talk to anyone in the next two hours.

42:47.080 --> 42:52.080
Like on the sessions, I don't have a target topic where I need to network with people.

42:52.120 --> 43:03.120
So I just, I leave, I find a nice coffee shop somewhere outside of the convention center getting some fresh air and just saying that that's okay.

43:03.120 --> 43:19.120
Also like once you get into the environment and you start to know more people, you don't have to go to every single social event after the conference because there's usually happy hours every evening.

43:19.160 --> 43:22.160
You don't have to go to all of them.

43:22.160 --> 43:30.160
Once you have a base network, then you can pick which one you want to go and the rest don't sweat on it.

43:30.160 --> 43:36.160
Because at the very beginning, I was like, my company's, company's sending me like overseas.

43:36.160 --> 43:40.160
It's a very expensive trip. I'm missing a week of work.

43:40.200 --> 43:44.200
Like the day job kind of work.

43:44.200 --> 43:51.200
And I felt obligated to go to every session, talk to people, go to every social event.

43:51.200 --> 43:57.200
And like if I stepped outside of the convention center during the conference day, then I felt guilty.

43:57.200 --> 44:01.200
So letting that go, yeah, let it go.

44:01.200 --> 44:06.200
It's very important for you to take care of yourself first.

44:06.240 --> 44:14.240
I mean, in addition to social awkwardness that I also deal with, I mean, it's just like crowded conferences like this.

44:14.240 --> 44:19.240
It's challenging to find time to talk to people because they're all busy, especially with speakers.

44:19.240 --> 44:21.240
And I've been on both sides of this.

44:21.240 --> 44:27.240
It's completely okay to say, could I message you on LinkedIn and have a call with them like a week later.

44:27.240 --> 44:30.240
And I actually did that with one of the speakers last year.

44:30.280 --> 44:35.280
This is one of the, like it was in the K building, one of the larger sessions.

44:35.280 --> 44:37.280
And he was just inundated with a lot of people.

44:37.280 --> 44:41.280
And I just said, hey, can I, can I connect you with you on LinkedIn?

44:41.280 --> 44:45.280
And then you're going to be in a more relaxed environment on Zoom.

44:45.280 --> 44:49.280
You just have a conversation about his talk or his background.

44:49.280 --> 44:54.280
So there are, you know, you don't, don't force yourself to just have all the conversations in two days.

44:54.280 --> 44:56.280
It's just very difficult logistically.

